{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Identification and Analysis of Bias in LLMsStudies within this theme have consistently demonstrated that LLMs can inherit and amplify biases present in their training data, affecting their language generation and decisionmaking processes [4], [8], [23]- [25].",
    "A common finding across several studies is that biases related to gender, race, and ethnicity are particularly prevalent, often leading to stereotypical or prejudicial outputs [12], [20], [21], [26], [27].",
    "Research has also shown that those biases are not merely surface-level issues but deeply embedded in the models' representations and embeddings [28]- [30].",
    "Comparative analyses have highlighted significant variances in bias across different models, suggesting that model architecture and training datasets play crucial roles in bias formation [31]- [33].",
    "Efforts to quantify bias through various metrics have led to the development of standardized benchmarks, enabling a more systematic evaluation of biases across models [19], [22], [34]- [36]."
  ],
